<subSubSection type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageNumber="401">
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181860" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole citrina Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole citrina Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="401" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="citrina">Pheidole citrina</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel rank="species">new species</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="401">Types Mus. Comp. Zool. Harvard.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="etymology">
<paragraph pageNumber="401">
Etymology L 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181860" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole citrina Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole citrina Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="401" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="citrina">citrina</taxonomicName>
, of citron, referring to yellow body color.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageNumber="401">
Diagnosis A very small, yellow member of the 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33744" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole flavens Roger" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole flavens Roger" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="401" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavens">flavens</taxonomicName>
group whose major is marked by its strongly curved propodeal spine (as though the tip had &quot;melted&quot; backward); long scapes, which reach the occipital comers; all of the sculpturing on the anterior half of the head consisting of longitudinal carinulae, with the posterior half smooth and shiny; and pronotal humerus in dorsal-oblique view rounded. Similar to 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181916" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole onyx Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole onyx Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="401" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="onyx">onyx</taxonomicName>
, but in the major, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181860" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole citrina Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole citrina Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="401" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="citrina">citrina</taxonomicName>
has a more curved propodeal spine, far less carinulation on the dorsal head surface, and longer scapes, among other differences. See also the less similar 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181879" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole grex Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole grex Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="401" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="grex">grex</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181984" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole humida Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole humida Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="401" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="humida">humida</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="description">
<paragraph pageNumber="401">Measurements (mm) Holotype major: HW 0.66, HL 0.70, SL 0.54, EL 0.06, PW 0.38.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="401">Paratype minor: HW 0.46, HL 0.50, SL 0.54, EL 0.10, PW 0.28.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="401">Color Major and minor: concolorous yellow.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="distribution">
<paragraph pageNumber="401">Range Atlantic lowlands of Costa Rica (Longino 1997).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
